Cork, Irska"},"cs":{"um 1225–Juni 1275":"okolo 1225–červen 1275","1221–1254":"1221–1254","1249–Female":"1249–Zesnulá","1225–1275":"1225–1275","1249":"1249","       1249":"1249","1225":"1225","1254":"1254","1221":"1221","1275":"1275","Juni 1275":"červen 1275","um 1225":"okolo 1225","Buttevant, County Cork, Ireland":"Buttevant, County Cork, Irsko","Ireland":"Irsko","Olethan,Cork,Ireland":"Olethan, County Cork, Irsko","Cork, County Cork, Irland":"Cork, County Cork, Irsko"},"da":{"um 1225–Juni 1275":"omkring 1225–juni 1275","1221–1254":"1221–1254","1249–Female":"1249–Afdød","1225–1275":"1225–1275","1249":"1249","       1249":"1249","1225":"1225","1254":"1254","1221":"1221","1275":"1275","Juni 1275":"juni 1275","um 1225":"omkring 1225","Buttevant, County Cork, Ireland":"Buttevant, County Cork, Irland","Ireland":"Irland","Olethan,Cork,Ireland":"Olethan, County Cork, Irland","Cork, County Cork, Irland":"Cork, County Cork, Irland"},"nl":{"um 1225–Juni 1275":"circa 1225–juni 1275","1221–1254":"1221–1254","1249–Female":"1249–Overleden","1225–1275":"1225–1275","1249":"1249","       1249":"1249","1225":"1225","1254":"1254","1221":"1221","1275":"1275","Juni 1275":"juni 1275","um 1225":"circa 1225","Buttevant, County Cork, Ireland":"Buttevant, County Cork, Ierland","Ireland":"Ierland","Olethan,Cork,Ireland":"Olethan, County Cork, Ierland","Cork, County Cork, Irland":"Cork, County Cork, Ierland"},"en":{"um 1225–Juni 1275":"about 1225–June 1275","1221–1254":"1221–1254","1249–Female":"1249–Deceased","1225–1275":"1225–1275","1249":"1249","       1249":"1249","1225":"1225","1254":"1254","1221":"1221","1275":"1275","Juni 1275":"June 1275","um 1225":"about 1225","Buttevant, County Cork, Ireland":"Buttevant, County Cork, Ireland","Ireland":"Ireland","Olethan,Cork,Ireland":"Olethan, County Cork, Ireland","Cork, County Cork, Irland":"Cork, County Cork, Ireland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Barry","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Donal, Aidan, Ciaran, Eoin, John Patrick, Kaitlin, Kieran, Murphy, Aileen, Brigid, Caitlin.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Beargha</b> ‘descendant of <i>Beargh</i>’, a byname meaning ‘plunderer’.","Irish and Manx: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Báire</b> ‘descendant of <i>Báire</i>’, a short form of either of two Gaelic personal names, <i>Bairrfhionn</i> or <i>Fionnbharr</i>, both meaning ‘fair-topped’. This may also be the source of the Manx name <i>Barry</i>, whose family's main seat was Ballavarry in Kirk Andreas."],"variants":[{"name":"Barr","meanings":["Scottish (Glasgow) and northern Irish (Ulster): habitational name from any of various places in southwestern Scotland, in particular Ayrshire and Renfrewshire, named with Gaelic <i>barr</i> ‘height, hill’ or a Brittonic cognate of this.","English and Welsh: habitational name from Great Barr in Staffordshire. This is from Brittonic <i>barro-</i> ‘top, summit’, referring to Barr Beacon; there is evidence that this was known as <i>la Bare</i> in the 13th century.","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Barre-en-Ouche in Eure, France, or perhaps from Barre-de-Semilly in Manche, France."]},{"name":"Barrie","meanings":["Scottish (Angus): habitational name from Barry in Angus or from another place so named, generally named with Gaelic <i>barr</i> ‘height, hill’, or from a British cognate of this word. This name is also the Scottish form of   Barry  .","French (<b>Barrié</b>): variant of   Barrier  .","Altered form of French   Baril  . Compare   Barry   7."]},{"name":"Berry","meanings":["Irish and Manx: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Béara</b> ‘descendant of <i>Béara</i>’, a personal name of unexplained etymology; or, in some cases, perhaps an Anglicized form of Irish and Manx <b>Ó Beargha</b>. Compare   Barry   1.","Scottish and northern Irish: variant of   Barrie  .","English: habitational name from any of several places called in Devon named with Old English <i>byrig</i>, dative case of <i>burh</i> ‘fortified manor house, stronghold’, such as Berry Pomeroy and Berrynarbor."]},{"name":"Dubarry","meanings":["French: variant of the topographic or habitational name   Barry  , with fused preposition and definite article <i>du</i> ‘from the’."]},{"name":"Baril","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Marcel, Andre, Normand, Alain, Armand, Ghislaine, Jacques, Jean-Marc, Jean-Pierre, Lucien, Monique, Phillippe.","French: from Old French <i>baril</i> ‘barrel’, applied as a metonymic occupational name for a cooper, or a nickname for a rotund man. Compare   Barry   7 and   Berry   7.","History: Jean Baril from the Saintonge region of France was in QC by 1673, when he married Marie Guillet, the first of his three wives. He died in 1724 in Batiscan, QC. His descendants also bear altered forms of the surname, such as <i>Barrie</i>, <i>Bar(r)y</i>, and <i>Berry</i>."]},{"name":"Bary","meanings":["Walloon and northern French: variant of   Barry   8.","French (southern): rare variant of   Barry   6.","Altered form of French   Baril  . Compare   Barry   7."]}]},{"name":"David","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by the greatest of all the kings of Israel, whose history is recounted with great vividness in the first and second books of Samuel and elsewhere. As a boy he killed the giant Philistine Goliath with his slingshot. As king of Judah, and later of all Israel, he expanded the power of the Israelites and established the security of their kingdom. He was also noted as a poet, many of the Psalms being attributed to him. The Hebrew derivation of the name is uncertain; it is said by some to represent a nursery word meaning ‘darling’. It is a very popular Jewish name, but is almost equally common among Gentiles in the English-speaking world. It is particularly common in Wales and Scotland, having been borne by the patron saint of Wales (  see  Dewi   ) and by two medieval kings of Scotland."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"David de Barry was born about 1225, in Buttevant, County Cork, Ireland. He had at least 1 daughter with Maud Bolton. He died in June 1275, in Cork, County Cork, Ireland, at the age of 51."},"et":{"um 1225–Juni 1275":"umbes 1225–juuni 1275","1221–1254":"1221–1254","1249–Female":"1249–Surnud","1225–1275":"1225–1275","1249":"1249","       1249":"1249","1225":"1225","1254":"1254","1221":"1221","1275":"1275","Juni 1275":"juuni 1275","um 1225":"umbes 1225","Buttevant, County Cork, Ireland":"Buttevant, County Cork, Iirimaa","Ireland":"Iirimaa","Olethan,Cork,Ireland":"Olethan, County Cork, Iirimaa","Cork, County Cork, Irland":"Cork, County Cork, Iirimaa"},"fi":{"um 1225–Juni 1275":"noin 1225–kesäkuu 1275","1221–1254":"1221–1254","1249–Female":"1249–Kuollut","1225–1275":"1225–1275","1249":"1249","       1249":"1249","1225":"1225","1254":"1254","1221":"1221","1275":"1275","Juni 1275":"kesäkuu 1275","um 1225":"noin 1225","Buttevant, County Cork, Ireland":"Buttevant, County Cork, Irlanti","Ireland":"Irlanti","Olethan,Cork,Ireland":"Olethan, County Cork, Irlanti","Cork, County Cork, Irland":"Cork, County Cork, Irlanti"},"fr":{"um 1225–Juni 1275":"environ 1225–juin 1275","1221–12